WEBVTT

00:01.543 --> 00:02.793
[Mabel Mora]
<i>Who is Dudenoff?</i>

00:02.794 --> 00:04.212
Do you know who's out to get me?

00:04.213 --> 00:05.671
[Helga] [on radio]
<i>The last person who came around</i>

00:05.672 --> 00:07.256
<i>asking these questions got killed.</i>

00:07.257 --> 00:10.009
We're illegally subletting
rent-controlled apartments.

00:10.010 --> 00:13.221
Professor Dudenoff retired to Portugal.
We send him rent.

00:13.222 --> 00:14.722
The voice on the ham radio said--

00:14.723 --> 00:17.225
- That was Helga, my ex-girlfriend,
- Your crazy ex-girlfriend.

00:17.226 --> 00:20.645
You may have heard about our little
"firearms moment" at the photo shoot.

00:20.646 --> 00:21.812
- [gunshot]
- [people screaming]

00:21.813 --> 00:23.022
It's Glen! He's still alive!

00:23.023 --> 00:25.483
[Zach Galifianakis]
They got me in my fat!

00:25.484 --> 00:27.401
Dudenoff? He's been cashing
social security checks

00:27.402 --> 00:29.111
at a bodega on 125th Street.

00:29.112 --> 00:30.905
[Mabel]
There's two left shoulders?

00:30.906 --> 00:34.075
Sazz's body wasn't the only one
in the incinerator.

00:34.076 --> 00:36.786
It belongs... to Dudenoff.

00:36.787 --> 00:38.788
Oliver, I wanna marry you.

00:38.789 --> 00:40.998
Whosever cashing
Dudenoff's checks is after you.

00:40.999 --> 00:44.085
Your friend Howard says
he knows who killed Dudenoff.

00:44.086 --> 00:46.671
<i>Wasn't just one person cashing his checks</i>.

00:46.672 --> 00:49.006
<i>He found five different signatures</i>

00:49.007 --> 00:51.050
<i>- with one phone number.</i>
- Hello?

00:51.051 --> 00:52.219
[Howard gasps]

00:53.846 --> 00:55.347
They know.

00:59.142 --> 01:01.144
[artillery exploding]

01:01.562 --> 01:05.147
[Milton Dudenoff]
<i>Alfred Hitchcock's</i> Lifeboat <i>is a film</i>

01:05.148 --> 01:10.111
<i>set entirely in a small boat
filled with disparate characters</i>

01:10.112 --> 01:13.865
<i>who learn how far they'd go
to survive the rough waters</i>

01:13.866 --> 01:15.658
<i>of their perilous circumstances.</i>

01:15.659 --> 01:17.243
[♪ jaunty music playing]

01:17.244 --> 01:18.828
<i>In New York City,</i>

01:18.829 --> 01:23.624
<i>a lifeboat can look a lot like
an affordable apartment in a nice building</i>

01:23.625 --> 01:25.751
<i>on the Upper West Side.</i>

01:25.752 --> 01:27.211
[Vince Fish]
Can I go in this way?

01:27.212 --> 01:28.296
[pedestrian]
Hey, taxi!

01:28.297 --> 01:29.380
[elevator doors shut]

01:29.381 --> 01:32.342
[♪ jaunty music continues]

01:35.554 --> 01:38.515
- [elevator dings]
- Well, I can make another tape. I c--

01:39.850 --> 01:42.810
- Hey!
- Hey. Call-- call me back.

01:42.811 --> 01:45.271
You got one of those fancy invites
from Dudenoff, too, huh?

01:45.272 --> 01:48.024
Yeah, it's so, uh, "murder mystery."

01:48.025 --> 01:50.151
I think it was delivered by a raven.

01:50.152 --> 01:53.238
- Is your eye okay?
- Yeah, it's probably just allergies.

01:54.072 --> 01:55.990
Hey! You guys got an invite, too?

01:55.991 --> 01:57.867
[laughs] Yeah. Check out this cardstock.

01:57.868 --> 02:00.954
He knows we can, like, text, right?

02:02.164 --> 02:03.623
Is someone gonna knock already?

02:03.624 --> 02:06.334
[in European accent]
Wait for me! Wait for me!

02:06.335 --> 02:08.419
- Helga!
- I brought my new girlfriend.

02:08.420 --> 02:10.087
I hope that is okay.

02:10.088 --> 02:12.632
Of course.
Who would turn away Hammy Faye Bakker?

02:12.633 --> 02:14.467
[Inez]
Piggy in a blanket!

02:14.468 --> 02:15.844
[Hammy squeals]

02:18.514 --> 02:19.597
Oh, hell!

02:19.598 --> 02:21.390
Look who it is.

02:21.391 --> 02:23.977
Come on in. Make yourself comfortable.

02:24.561 --> 02:26.979
I'm about to change your lives.

02:26.980 --> 02:30.066
[♪ lively theme song playing]

02:30.067 --> 02:33.153
[♪ vocalizing]

03:11.984 --> 03:13.318
[♪ theme song fades out]

03:14.403 --> 03:18.198
- [♪ curious music playing]
- [car engine starting]

03:19.074 --> 03:21.242
[Charles-Haden Savage]
One thing about choosing a safe house

03:21.243 --> 03:22.411
filled with your family.

03:22.870 --> 03:24.371
[Oliver Putnam]
What's that, Charles?

03:25.038 --> 03:28.541
[Charles] It makes going home to a
building full of murderers more appealing.

03:28.542 --> 03:30.210
- [car sputtering]
- [Oliver grunts]

03:34.131 --> 03:36.132
- [car hissing, rattling]
- [Mabel] Seriously?

03:36.133 --> 03:38.886
[Oliver] [coughing gags]
Okay, just put-- [sighs]

03:39.761 --> 03:43.055
[sighs] No, no, no.
Charles, use your hips.

03:43.056 --> 03:45.391
Up and around like a hula hoop.
Do this thing.

03:45.392 --> 03:47.351
- [Charles] It's not helping.
- Would you just let me?

03:47.352 --> 03:50.438
No, I can do it. It's just a problem
with the, uh, th-the fuselage.

03:50.439 --> 03:52.815
How do neither of you know how
to pop the hood of a car?

03:52.816 --> 03:56.569
- Because real men hire other men, Mabel.
- Triple-A says they're 15 minutes away,

03:56.570 --> 03:59.447
and it's good to leave them something
to do 'cause it makes 'em happy.

03:59.448 --> 04:02.534
- You're a real philanthropist. Hang on.
- [musical ring tone]

04:03.035 --> 04:05.870
[groans] They're calling again! Ignore!

04:05.871 --> 04:08.831
- [Oliver mutters, sniffs]
- Well, while we're waiting,

04:08.832 --> 04:10.833
we should probably do a recap.

04:10.834 --> 04:12.460
Here's what we know so far.

04:12.461 --> 04:15.254
This Dudenoff guy has a bunch
of rent-controlled units,

04:15.255 --> 04:17.173
and he moved the Westies in.

04:17.174 --> 04:21.010
Then, even though they need him alive
to keep their homes,

04:21.011 --> 04:23.012
they kill and burn him.

04:23.013 --> 04:25.014
And then, they cash
his checks to cover it up.

04:25.015 --> 04:29.060
And when poor Sazz caught onto them,
they shot her from Dudenoff's apartment.

04:29.061 --> 04:30.853
And then, they shot at me, barely missing

04:30.854 --> 04:33.147
the most essential person
to our investigative work.

04:33.148 --> 04:35.191
I can't believe Vince Fish would do this!

04:35.192 --> 04:36.859
He was my Wordle buddy!

04:36.860 --> 04:39.779
- [ringtone plays]
- Oh! [growls] Hold on.

04:39.780 --> 04:42.406
Oh. Th-They're FaceTiming us now.

04:42.407 --> 04:43.824
- [FaceTime answers]
- Hello?

04:43.825 --> 04:47.828
<i>Hey, guys! So the sexy half
of this crime-solving sextet</i>

04:47.829 --> 04:49.330
has some thoughts.

04:49.331 --> 04:51.332
<i>Don't you have to go to rehearsal?</i>

04:51.333 --> 04:53.876
Now that we know that we're indispensable,
we cannot leave you alone.

04:53.877 --> 04:55.962
<i>We are professional investigators,</i>

04:55.963 --> 04:58.172
<i>and you are playing us
in a movie because of it!</i>

04:58.173 --> 04:59.632
<i>We are fine on our own!</i>

04:59.633 --> 05:01.884
Hey, can we just, uh,
mute you for a second?

05:01.885 --> 05:03.803
If you're muting us, we're muting you!

05:03.804 --> 05:05.556
[Zach] [on phone]
<i>Okay, good. Muting each other.</i>

05:06.223 --> 05:07.223
[Zach sighs]

05:07.224 --> 05:08.933
<i>Are these dumb-dumbs gonna ruin this?</i>

05:08.934 --> 05:11.102
Uh, y-you didn't mute us.

05:11.103 --> 05:13.938
<i>Oh, sorry about that. Uh, muting now.</i>

05:13.939 --> 05:16.732
- What happened? I'm muted. [snorts]
- [Eva Longoria] <i>No, we can still hear you.</i>

05:16.733 --> 05:19.068
Tell you what? Let's just not mute!

05:19.069 --> 05:21.112
[over phone]
<i>We need to find someplace safe to plan.</i>

05:21.113 --> 05:23.155
Anywhere but the Arconia.

05:23.156 --> 05:24.740
[♪ curious music playing]

05:24.741 --> 05:27.368
Okay. I know just the place.

05:27.369 --> 05:28.911
[car hissing]

05:28.912 --> 05:30.372
♪

05:32.709 --> 05:34.750
Okay, but how do we get a confession?

05:34.751 --> 05:38.087
Well, I have an idea,
but it involves someone.

05:38.088 --> 05:40.715
- Swear to God, if you say Tony Danza--
- It's Tony Danza.

05:40.716 --> 05:43.759
Eugene, can we go one day
without you mentioning Tony Danza?

05:43.760 --> 05:44.886
[production set chatter]

05:44.887 --> 05:45.971
[Mabel]
Hey, look.

05:47.598 --> 05:50.391
[Oliver gasps, laughs weakly]

05:50.392 --> 05:52.186
[Charles]
How could my character live here?

05:52.561 --> 05:54.771
The albums, not alphabetized.

05:55.856 --> 05:57.106
Oh! Nice.

05:57.107 --> 06:00.985
Nice.
A first edition touching a second edition!

06:00.986 --> 06:03.322
Yeah, brilliant. That's really good.

06:04.323 --> 06:05.324
Oh, really?

06:07.409 --> 06:09.911
- [Oliver] Oh.
- [Zach] Okay.

06:09.912 --> 06:11.871
So, we bust in on the Westies
with two celebrities

06:11.872 --> 06:13.581
- and Eugene.
- [Eva] Mm-hmm.

06:13.582 --> 06:14.665
Then, what?

06:14.666 --> 06:16.125
It's almost go-time on the movie,

06:16.126 --> 06:18.085
so I'm gonna pump my cheeks
while we spitball.

06:18.086 --> 06:20.129
- Can we get back to my idea for a minute?
- [Zach exhales]

06:20.130 --> 06:21.214
Because it's so simple.

06:21.215 --> 06:23.841
We invite the Westies to, yes,

06:23.842 --> 06:26.344
Tony Danza's 35th annual

06:26.345 --> 06:28.804
"It's Time To Wear White Pants
Extrava-Danza."

06:28.805 --> 06:32.558
Tony Danza was a 1980s television star of
<i>Who's the Boss?</i>

06:32.559 --> 06:34.936
- I don't care. It's okay.
- [Oliver] Oh.

06:34.937 --> 06:37.522
Then, we tell the Sauce Family
that Tony wants

06:37.523 --> 06:40.233
to start his own line of sauces called

06:40.234 --> 06:41.609
"Who's the Sauce?"

06:41.610 --> 06:44.445
The Westies will then spill their story

06:44.446 --> 06:48.699
on account of Danza's, uh,
neighborhood wise-guy charisma.

06:48.700 --> 06:51.369
- Danza's the perfect plan-za.
- Mm.

06:51.370 --> 06:52.745
I love it. I love it.

06:52.746 --> 06:55.081
I would change it slightly
and maybe not do it.

06:55.082 --> 06:58.585
And instead,
surprise them with a ding-dong.

06:59.586 --> 07:02.255
- Wh-What...?
- Uh, say more about the ding-dong.

07:02.256 --> 07:06.133
In soapy TV,
a "ding-dong" is a-a sexy surprise.

07:06.134 --> 07:08.886
It's like a-a long-lost brother returns,

07:08.887 --> 07:11.264
or, uh, your paralyzed uncle

07:11.265 --> 07:13.349
starts to walk again after 40 years.

07:13.350 --> 07:14.851
Y-You're overthinking it.

07:14.852 --> 07:17.937
One of them snapped, killed Dudenoff,
and the others are covering for 'em.

07:17.938 --> 07:19.438
All we need to do is get them talking.

07:19.439 --> 07:21.524
I say that we invite the Westies

07:21.525 --> 07:24.110
to a celebrity-studded...

07:24.111 --> 07:26.487
super-sized game of Oh Hell at Oliver's.

07:26.488 --> 07:27.822
That's good.

07:27.823 --> 07:30.199
Right. Our own turf.
The key is to remain calm.

07:30.200 --> 07:33.160
Well, having precise control
of our emotions

07:33.161 --> 07:35.162
is what actors do best.

07:35.163 --> 07:36.873
Yeah, the question is can you three do it?

07:36.874 --> 07:38.916
First of all, I am an actor!

07:38.917 --> 07:40.042
Well, let's not go crazy.

07:40.043 --> 07:43.838
But also, I'm entirely capable
of catching the killer of my dear friend

07:43.839 --> 07:46.884
who only wanted to open
a trampoline park so young--

07:51.847 --> 07:53.472
I need to lie down.

07:53.473 --> 07:56.184
[production set chatter continues]

07:56.185 --> 07:59.229
Where the fuck is my bedroom?!

07:59.980 --> 08:01.856
- [Oliver growls]
- [♪ gentle plucky music playing]

08:01.857 --> 08:03.983
[Mabel]
I hope Charles can hold it together.

08:03.984 --> 08:07.445
Confronting a friend's killer
just brings up a lotta shit.

08:07.446 --> 08:10.032
[device buzzing]

08:11.116 --> 08:12.117
[Oliver growls]

08:12.492 --> 08:14.869
Oh, sorry. Just tightening my pores

08:14.870 --> 08:18.915
with the Lady Longoria 19-in-1 Multitool.

08:18.916 --> 08:20.500
This is the infrared setting.

08:20.501 --> 08:22.293
Yeah, it's also a nail gun,

08:22.294 --> 08:25.296
has a Phillips head, and a vibrating head.

08:25.297 --> 08:27.924
- [Oliver laughs]
- [cell phone ringing]

08:27.925 --> 08:29.926
- Hello?
- [Loretta Durkin] [on phone] <i>Hi!</i>

08:29.927 --> 08:32.720
- Oh, hey, baby. It's my fiancée.
- [Loretta giggles]

08:32.721 --> 08:35.806
We're getting married
this weekend! [laughs]

08:35.807 --> 08:37.683
[in Cary Grant impression]
Hello, my darling love.

08:37.684 --> 08:38.768
This weekend?

08:38.769 --> 08:41.854
I know, he's a little old
to have a shotgun wedding.

08:41.855 --> 08:44.942
Yeah. More like a musket wedding.
[wheezing laugh]

08:47.444 --> 08:48.695
Where did he go?

08:49.363 --> 08:50.363
[multitool buzzing stops]

08:50.364 --> 08:53.032
Hey, look, it's also a recorder.

08:53.033 --> 08:54.117
[clicks button]

08:54.535 --> 08:56.787
[sing-songy]
<i>♪ Eva, you're a genius! ♪</i>

08:57.579 --> 08:59.956
[recorder plays] [auto-tuned]
<i>♪ Eva, you're a genius! ♪</i>

08:59.957 --> 09:02.834
It has auto-tune. [giggles]
You wanna try it?

09:02.835 --> 09:05.921
Uh, don't--
Definitely don't wanna touch that.

09:06.713 --> 09:08.215
[clicks button, buzzing resumes]

09:08.799 --> 09:09.924
- Yeah. Okay.
- [Loretta] <i>Yeah.</i>

09:09.925 --> 09:12.176
No, no, honey. I-I will--
I will handle it all.

09:12.177 --> 09:14.303
- [Loretta] <i>I can't believe we're here.</i>
- I know. It's exciting.

09:14.304 --> 09:15.763
Uh, no, I'll,
I'll make the arrangements.

09:15.764 --> 09:17.431
Okay, I love you, too. Goodbye.

09:17.432 --> 09:19.851
- [production set chatter]
- [Oliver sighs]

09:19.852 --> 09:20.936
[Zach]
Hey, that's my seat.

09:21.895 --> 09:23.896
Oh! [laughs] Of course it is.

09:23.897 --> 09:25.816
I, uh, I keep forgetting.

09:26.483 --> 09:28.693
- Okay.
- We getting married this weekend?

09:28.694 --> 09:29.986
I am.

09:29.987 --> 09:32.489
Please don't tell me
you're gonna do it at a courthouse.

09:33.407 --> 09:35.449
Weddings demand spectacle.

09:35.450 --> 09:38.286
Music, speeches, AK-47s
shot right up in the air.

09:38.287 --> 09:40.414
Zach, I didn't realize
you were a fellow romantic.

09:40.956 --> 09:43.749
Weddings are the most
important part of a marriage.

09:43.750 --> 09:45.334
My wife and I get married quarterly.

09:45.335 --> 09:48.129
The venue sets the tone
for your life together.

09:48.130 --> 09:50.464
When we want playfulness,
we get married at the beach.

09:50.465 --> 09:52.341
If we've been fighting, then...

09:52.342 --> 09:54.343
it's at the site of
an important armistice.

09:54.344 --> 09:56.930
Yalta, Potsdam, Camp David.

09:57.556 --> 09:59.348
We needed a lot of those.

09:59.349 --> 10:02.935
- Well, Loretta said a courthouse is fine.
- Oh, she's right. It's perfect

10:02.936 --> 10:04.605
'cause you'll be right back there
for the divorce.

10:05.772 --> 10:06.772
- Zach?
- Yes.

10:06.773 --> 10:09.192
- We're rehearsing scene 13.
- Which one is that one?

10:09.193 --> 10:11.986
The one where Oliver explains
why his previous marriage failed.

10:11.987 --> 10:13.447
Oh.

10:14.239 --> 10:16.241
- [set bell rings]
- [set chatter continues]

10:17.826 --> 10:19.452
Are you okay, Charles?

10:19.453 --> 10:22.914
I-I don't think I've ever seen you angry.

10:22.915 --> 10:26.502
And to be honest, it would layer
my performance if I could, uh,

10:27.211 --> 10:28.753
see what it looks like.

10:28.754 --> 10:31.005
Well, uh, yes, I am angry. And no,

10:31.006 --> 10:33.007
uh, you'll not see what it looks like

10:33.008 --> 10:35.676
because it's not socially acceptable.

10:35.677 --> 10:37.303
Eugene, you wanna practice
flipping omelets?

10:37.304 --> 10:39.805
Oh, the infamous omelet bit.
Yeah, yeah. Good. Thanks.

10:39.806 --> 10:41.182
I'll, uh, practice. Anyway,

10:41.183 --> 10:44.060
I'm curious. I mean,
a-are-are you a yeller?

10:44.061 --> 10:46.562
- Do you get violent?
- Oh, no. Worse.

10:46.563 --> 10:48.814
But it hasn't happened
in decades because of my

10:48.815 --> 10:51.275
emotion suppression technique,

10:51.276 --> 10:55.071
which involves breathing and a lot of,

10:55.072 --> 10:57.157
uh, room straightening.

10:58.450 --> 10:59.451
[omelet splats]

10:59.952 --> 11:00.953
[Charles gasps]

11:06.500 --> 11:09.877
[♪ gentle plucky music playing]

11:09.878 --> 11:11.421
There you go.

11:12.130 --> 11:13.131
[Eugene clears throat]

11:14.132 --> 11:15.133
This bother you?

11:17.135 --> 11:18.637
- No.
- This bother you?

11:20.389 --> 11:22.598
- No.
- [Eugene Levy] Does this bother you?

11:22.599 --> 11:24.141
Why are you doing that?

11:24.142 --> 11:25.602
- Does this...
- [Charles yelps]

11:30.274 --> 11:32.484
♪

11:35.028 --> 11:36.363
[quiet street noise]

11:36.905 --> 11:38.906
Okay, they'll be here any minute.

11:38.907 --> 11:41.367
Now, I know we're all running hot.
We have a podcast,

11:41.368 --> 11:43.953
two murders, a wedding,

11:43.954 --> 11:45.204
but we're gonna stay calm.

11:45.205 --> 11:47.415
Well, we can stay calm way more
than you can stay calm.

11:47.416 --> 11:50.043
- It's not a competition.
- It's now a competition.

11:50.586 --> 11:52.795
I've set my sphincter to clenching,

11:52.796 --> 11:55.298
- unclenching, re-clenching.
- [knocking on door]

11:55.299 --> 11:57.384
- It's them. It's them.
- Okay. Okay.

11:59.094 --> 12:01.679
Maybe I could throw together
a wedding booze cruise.

12:01.680 --> 12:03.347
That's the blueprint
you want for your marriage?

12:03.348 --> 12:05.183
You're freezing, you end up nowhere,

12:05.184 --> 12:06.601
and the maid of honor fucks the skipper?

12:06.602 --> 12:08.519
- [knocking on door]
- [Oliver snorts]

12:08.520 --> 12:10.772
- [Charles] Come on, come on, come on.
- Yeah. Yeah. Yeah.

12:13.692 --> 12:14.693
[knocking]

12:17.196 --> 12:19.030
Oh, hell-o!

12:19.031 --> 12:20.406
[laughter]

12:20.407 --> 12:22.033
We brought snacks.

12:22.034 --> 12:24.452
[Inez]
Can't play cards without <i>jamón!</i>

12:24.453 --> 12:26.162
[Alfonso]
That's right, <i>mami.</i>

12:26.163 --> 12:27.705
Okay. Well, thanks, guys, for coming.

12:27.706 --> 12:29.540
We figured we'd host
since it's a big group.

12:29.541 --> 12:32.376
Ah, please.
Any friends of yours are friends of ours.

12:32.377 --> 12:34.712
Especially if they're Hollywood stars.

12:34.713 --> 12:37.465
- [laughter]
- You can't tell 'cause of the eye patch,

12:37.466 --> 12:39.509
but I'm winking playfully.

12:39.510 --> 12:40.593
[laughter]

12:40.594 --> 12:42.220
- [door slams, lock clicks]
- [Mabel and Eva gasp]

12:42.221 --> 12:43.429
Let's go.

12:43.430 --> 12:44.555
[knife slices]

12:44.556 --> 12:46.516
We know you know about the checks.

12:46.517 --> 12:48.601
Give us your phones now!

12:48.602 --> 12:51.437
[♪ dramatic music playing]

12:51.438 --> 12:52.522
[Oliver grumbles]

12:52.523 --> 12:54.524
♪

12:54.525 --> 12:55.608
[Eva mutters]

12:55.609 --> 12:58.737
♪

13:01.787 --> 13:03.908
[♪ suspenseful music playing]

13:03.909 --> 13:06.494
- So, what's your move now, Vince?
- [Vince] You're gonna sit there,

13:06.495 --> 13:08.538
you're gonna listen to our story.

13:08.539 --> 13:10.457
Okay, everyone on my team, stay calm.

13:11.083 --> 13:13.960
Although killers do always tell you
their story before they kill you.

13:13.961 --> 13:18.464
They're gonna try to humanize themselves
with long origin stories.

13:18.465 --> 13:20.842
Exactly. Like if we had gone through that,

13:20.843 --> 13:22.802
we would've killed
and eaten Dudenoff, too.

13:22.803 --> 13:25.264
- We didn't eat him.
- Yeah, but you killed him, right?

13:27.099 --> 13:29.101
Okay. So,

13:29.685 --> 13:31.895
Dudenoff used to come to our restaurant.

13:32.271 --> 13:35.398
Milton and his wife were regulars,
until she passed.

13:35.399 --> 13:37.942
Then, he started ordering in.

13:37.943 --> 13:41.445
And when we were understaffed,
we delivered to him on our way home.

13:41.446 --> 13:43.614
Oh, hell!
- [indistinct chatter]

13:43.615 --> 13:45.908
[Ana]
<i>He looked so alone in his little studio.</i>

13:45.909 --> 13:49.453
[Inez] <i>He invited us in.
We started playing cards.</i>

13:49.454 --> 13:52.039
[Alfonso]
<i>Oh Hell on Friday nights.</i>

13:52.040 --> 13:53.875
<i>It started to become a regular thing.</i>

13:53.876 --> 13:56.085
- [Dudenoff] Please, please.
- Okay. So, the, uh,

13:56.086 --> 14:00.131
the secret ingredient here
is <i>Jamón Ibérico.</i>

14:00.132 --> 14:03.718
- Oh, well, nobody makes it like you do.
- [Alfonso] Oh, thank you.

14:03.719 --> 14:05.595
Our dream, actually, is to, uh,

14:05.596 --> 14:08.639
start our own line of sauces.
And I-I know this sounds crazy,

14:08.640 --> 14:11.184
but Tony Danza would be an investor.

14:11.185 --> 14:12.268
[soft laughter]

14:12.269 --> 14:13.519
[Eugene]
<i>So, you killed him</i>

14:13.520 --> 14:18.399
because he didn't deliver
the last piece of the dream?

14:18.400 --> 14:20.318
Don't say Tony Danza.

14:20.319 --> 14:22.236
Sauce Dad said it first!

14:22.237 --> 14:23.905
- We didn't kill him!
- Never.

14:23.906 --> 14:25.781
- Yeah. We definitely did not kill him.
- We loved him.

14:25.782 --> 14:28.409
- Then, Crazy Rudy killed him.
- Crazy? Me?

14:28.410 --> 14:31.787
[♪ "Deck The Halls" playing from sweater]

14:31.788 --> 14:32.914
[Rudy sighs]

14:32.915 --> 14:34.875
I don't know why I keep
replacing the battery.

14:36.001 --> 14:37.377
Lovely.

14:38.128 --> 14:40.588
I met Professor Dudenoff eight years ago.

14:40.589 --> 14:42.215
I was trying to be an actor,

14:42.216 --> 14:45.009
I was holding down five jobs,
and I signed up for his class.

14:45.010 --> 14:46.511
I remember my first acting class.

14:46.512 --> 14:47.929
It was a film class.

14:47.930 --> 14:51.015
It was in a closet of a basement
of a subway stop.

14:51.016 --> 14:52.976
Most of my scene partners
were sex workers.

14:54.102 --> 14:55.311
[Rudy Thurber]
Okay. [clears throat]

14:55.312 --> 14:59.148
One day, we watched <i>A Few Good Men</i>
in Professor Dudenoff's class.

14:59.149 --> 15:01.609
I ran up to him afterwards on the street,
and I said,

15:01.610 --> 15:05.112
I'd studied a monologue from
that film for my previous class.

15:05.113 --> 15:07.740
He asked me to do it, and I did.

15:07.741 --> 15:10.743
I did the whole thing,
right there at the bus stop.

15:10.744 --> 15:13.037
- It went something like this.
- Oh...

15:13.038 --> 15:14.789
"You want answers?"
"I think I'm entitled."

15:14.790 --> 15:16.666
"You want answers?"
"I want the truth!"

15:16.667 --> 15:18.835
- "You can't handle the truth!
- [Oliver mouthing along]

15:18.836 --> 15:20.336
"Son, we live in a world that has walls,

15:20.337 --> 15:22.380
"and those walls need to be
guarded by men with guns.

15:22.381 --> 15:23.464
"Who's gonna do it? You?

15:23.465 --> 15:25.132
"You, Lieutenant Weinberg?

15:25.133 --> 15:26.259
I have a greater respons--"

15:26.260 --> 15:28.219
I-I'm sorry. Are you gonna do
the whole monologue?

15:28.220 --> 15:31.223
Yeah, I was gonna do the whole thing.
I think it's worth it.

15:32.307 --> 15:35.601
"I have a greater responsibility
than you can possibly fathom!

15:35.602 --> 15:37.228
"You weep for Santiago...
Saves lives...

15:37.229 --> 15:41.107
"My existence, while grotesque and
incomprehensible to you, saves lives.

15:41.108 --> 15:42.775
"You don't want the truth
because, deep down,

15:42.776 --> 15:44.819
"in places you don't
talk about at parties,

15:44.820 --> 15:46.654
"you want me on that wall!

15:46.655 --> 15:48.322
"You need me on that wall...

15:48.323 --> 15:50.449
"Otherwise, I suggest you pick up
a weapon and stand a post.

15:50.450 --> 15:54.203
Either way, I don't give a damn
what you think you're entitled to!"

15:54.204 --> 15:56.581
"Did you order the code red?"
"I did the job."

15:56.582 --> 15:59.333
"Did you order the code red?"
"You're goddamn right I did!"

15:59.334 --> 16:02.628
- Oh... Oh, that was wonderful.
- [Rudy panting]

16:02.629 --> 16:03.713
♪

16:03.714 --> 16:04.922
I blew his socks off.

16:04.923 --> 16:08.426
<i>And he invited me back
to his place at the Arconia.</i>

16:08.427 --> 16:10.511
- That's my jam.
- And this? What's this?

16:10.512 --> 16:12.597
Uh, that is a ham radio.

16:12.598 --> 16:14.140
What do you do with a ham radio?

16:14.141 --> 16:17.101
No, it's just-- it's just a hobby,
you know? A-And a very...

16:17.102 --> 16:19.604
[Rudy] <i>Of course,
I got my own ham radio.</i>

16:19.605 --> 16:21.272
<i>And ultimately, we all did.</i>

16:21.273 --> 16:23.441
And Professor Dudenoff looked at me.

16:23.442 --> 16:24.817
<i>He said...</i>

16:24.818 --> 16:26.944
You know, you're really very good, Rudy.

16:26.945 --> 16:28.905
Thank you. That...

16:28.906 --> 16:29.990
That means a lot to me.

16:31.658 --> 16:33.075
[sighing]

16:33.076 --> 16:34.661
Let me ask you somethin'.

16:35.204 --> 16:38.332
If your life were a movie,

16:39.791 --> 16:41.918
what would be your happy ending?

16:41.919 --> 16:44.462
And that's when he touched
your Santa sack,

16:44.463 --> 16:45.630
and you had your "happy ending."

16:45.631 --> 16:47.423
- [Mabel] Eva!
- [Eva] What?

16:47.424 --> 16:49.550
[Rudy]
No! I said I wanted to stay in the city,

16:49.551 --> 16:51.886
keep performing, keep trying,

16:51.887 --> 16:55.431
and live with fewer roommates
who use towels as toilet paper.

16:55.432 --> 16:57.934
That was my dream.

16:57.935 --> 17:01.020
So, Charles, that leaves

17:01.021 --> 17:02.772
your "friend" Vince.

17:02.773 --> 17:05.942
He exposed you to pink eye,
and what did you get?

17:05.943 --> 17:07.443
Lies!

17:07.444 --> 17:08.903
And, likely, pink eye.

17:08.904 --> 17:12.032
Come on, doesn't that make you... angry?

17:12.866 --> 17:14.492
[Charles quietly wheezes]

17:14.493 --> 17:16.244
Oh, I'm fine.

17:16.245 --> 17:17.411
I'm suppressing,

17:17.412 --> 17:19.580
and I'm suppressing, and suppressing,

17:19.581 --> 17:21.667
and I'm... good.

17:22.793 --> 17:25.503
Alright. Since none of you seem

17:25.504 --> 17:27.965
to be on the verge of a psychotic break.

17:28.841 --> 17:30.842
Before my wife died, she made me promise

17:30.843 --> 17:33.719
that I wouldn't turn into
one of those weird lonely old men.

17:33.720 --> 17:35.596
Now, we both loved movies,

17:35.597 --> 17:38.850
so when I saw Professor Dudenoff's flyer
for his film class,

17:38.851 --> 17:42.979
I thought that this way was her way
of telling me to go out and make friends.

17:42.980 --> 17:45.565
But, oh, those kids...

17:45.566 --> 17:49.360
[♪ "Auld Lang Syne" playing]

17:49.361 --> 17:53.407
<i>♪ Lang... Syne! ♪</i>

17:54.116 --> 17:56.617
- [♪ song ends]
- [Dudenoff] You know, the reason

17:56.618 --> 18:02.624
<i>It's A Wonderful Life</i> is timeless
comes down to one thing.

18:04.126 --> 18:06.502
Casting. You know,

18:06.503 --> 18:09.590
if you can populate your story

18:10.299 --> 18:11.800
with the right people,

18:13.260 --> 18:14.719
your work will live forever.

18:14.720 --> 18:17.430
[sighs]
Sorry, but the movie isn't timeless.

18:17.431 --> 18:19.223
It's pro-capitalist gaslighting!

18:19.224 --> 18:20.892
George Bailey's life still sucks,

18:20.893 --> 18:23.478
- and Potter just gets away with it.
- [Vince] [emotional] No!

18:24.271 --> 18:26.022
No, you missed the point! [sniffles]

18:26.023 --> 18:28.608
George ends up with his family.
Potter's all alone.

18:28.609 --> 18:30.776
- I like being alone.
- [scattered laughter]

18:30.777 --> 18:33.863
Well, excuse me, Mr. Life Experience.

18:33.864 --> 18:35.824
[sniffles] But being really alone?

18:37.326 --> 18:39.952
There's nothing worse.
You don't smile, you don't laugh,

18:39.953 --> 18:42.997
you stop caring about
what food tastes like 'cause...

18:42.998 --> 18:44.082
[sniffles]

18:45.083 --> 18:47.710
you still wake up alone again without her.

18:47.711 --> 18:48.794
Every class...

18:48.795 --> 18:51.088
<i>But Dudenoff, him I liked.</i>

18:51.089 --> 18:53.591
"...hates poor people.
This movie hates trees."

18:53.592 --> 18:55.259
Why do they have to be
so mad all the time?

18:55.260 --> 18:57.929
- This world's a dumpster fire.
- [Vince] It sure is.

18:57.930 --> 19:00.473
In this city, you know, kid,

19:00.474 --> 19:04.685
you can't even afford an apartment
unless Mommy and Daddy pay for it.

19:04.686 --> 19:08.105
- And why can't a movie just be a movie?
- [Dudenoff sighs]

19:08.106 --> 19:10.066
[♪ soft music playing]

19:10.067 --> 19:12.235
Jack Lemmon in <i>The Apartment.</i>
I-I-I didn't know that...

19:12.236 --> 19:14.737
[Vince] <i>And he invited me
to join his weekly card game.</i>

19:14.738 --> 19:16.197
[Dudenoff]
I-I feel empathetic.

19:16.198 --> 19:18.783
[Vince] <i>I had no idea
why he knew we'd click...</i>

19:18.784 --> 19:20.117
[muffled chatter]

19:20.118 --> 19:22.578
<i>- ...but we did.</i>
- [Rudy chuckles]

19:22.579 --> 19:25.748
<i>His wife had been a music teacher.
Back when the city was cheap,</i>

19:25.749 --> 19:28.209
<i>whenever a unit would
open up on their floor,</i>

19:28.210 --> 19:31.462
they would grab it. You know,
she'd use it for music classes or,

19:31.463 --> 19:35.008
you know, uh, let a kid stay there
if he was going through tough times.

19:35.759 --> 19:36.759
But with her gone,

19:36.760 --> 19:41.014
Professor Dudenoff was living
amid, um, an empty hallway.

19:41.765 --> 19:44.059
<i>He just couldn't bear to
give up those apartments.</i>

19:45.561 --> 19:48.355
<i>And one night,
after many hours of Oh Hell,</i>

19:50.941 --> 19:54.235
<i>he decided that
he wasn't going to turn into</i>

19:54.236 --> 19:57.322
<i>one of those weird lonely old men.</i>

19:58.866 --> 20:00.868
He broke the law for us,

20:01.326 --> 20:04.370
so that we could have
a chance at our dreams.

20:04.371 --> 20:06.163
But he had a dream, too.

20:06.164 --> 20:07.624
To live in Portugal.

20:08.125 --> 20:10.169
And he left. And, no,

20:10.836 --> 20:14.213
- we haven't heard from him since.
- [Alfonso] And, yes,

20:14.214 --> 20:16.674
we've been keeping up the ruse and...

20:16.675 --> 20:19.219
cashing his checks.

20:20.095 --> 20:21.888
So that's the whole thing?

20:21.889 --> 20:25.016
Yeah, we could do it again if you like.
I could do a comedy version if you want--

20:25.017 --> 20:26.434
[overlapping "Nos"]

20:26.435 --> 20:28.186
- Thank you.
- [Oliver] Oh God, no.

20:28.187 --> 20:30.480
- Okay, I think we're done here.
- [doorbell rings]

20:31.481 --> 20:32.482
Not yet.

20:34.151 --> 20:35.693
It's ding-dong time.

20:35.694 --> 20:38.112
[gasps] You pulled a ding-dong?

20:38.113 --> 20:39.447
- It was a good idea.
- [door opens]

20:39.448 --> 20:40.532
[♪ tense sting]

20:41.533 --> 20:43.744
- [door shuts]
- [♪ suspenseful music playing]

20:45.120 --> 20:47.122
- [Westies gasp]
- Helga?!

20:48.290 --> 20:49.707
What are you doing here?

20:49.708 --> 20:52.710
Mabel reached out on the ham radio.

20:52.711 --> 20:54.922
I'm here to tell the truth.

20:55.881 --> 20:58.175
We can't handle the truth.

21:01.388 --> 21:03.888
[♪ curious music playing]

21:03.889 --> 21:05.848
[Charles]
You're Helga?

21:05.849 --> 21:07.892
I imagined you toothless with a club.

21:07.893 --> 21:10.228
[scoffs] Disregard him, Helga.

21:10.229 --> 21:13.232
His brain is covered with plaque.
Please go on.

21:14.316 --> 21:17.860
I-I first met Dudenoff
when I'd just become a locksmith,

21:17.861 --> 21:19.654
which was my childhood dream.

21:19.655 --> 21:20.738
Wait? Really?

21:20.739 --> 21:24.116
No. Do I look like a locksmith? I'm hot.

21:24.117 --> 21:27.996
So, my father died
and left me the business.

21:28.747 --> 21:32.250
He was all I had until I met Dudenoff.

21:32.251 --> 21:35.838
[♪ muffled "Perfect Strangers"
theme song playing]

21:37.381 --> 21:38.841
[♪ Dudenoff humming along]

21:39.633 --> 21:41.133
[sings]
<i>♪ Standing tall ♪</i>

21:41.134 --> 21:43.052
You know, it's before your time,

21:43.053 --> 21:44.637
but that's the theme song to--

21:44.638 --> 21:47.181
It's <i>Perfect Strangers,</i> yes? I know.

21:47.182 --> 21:48.642
Yes.

21:49.393 --> 21:51.269
- Yeah.
- You know, I've never met anyone

21:51.270 --> 21:52.980
- who loses their keys this often.
- [lock clicks]

21:54.147 --> 21:57.483
Some people your age
put it on a retractable belt...

21:57.484 --> 22:00.529
It's not dementia.
I always lose my keys. I--

22:01.363 --> 22:04.615
My wife used to let me in, but...

22:04.616 --> 22:07.703
[♪ theme song continues]

22:08.996 --> 22:11.539
- Okay!
- [lock buzzes]

22:11.540 --> 22:13.291
- Ah, look at that.
- [Helga] So, uh,

22:13.292 --> 22:16.003
what is a code that someone
your age can remember?

22:17.921 --> 22:20.631
[sighs] How about, um,

22:20.632 --> 22:21.800
"Oh Hell"?

22:22.384 --> 22:24.051
Wait, like the card game?

22:24.052 --> 22:25.803
- You know it?
- [Helga] My father and I

22:25.804 --> 22:27.555
used to play all the time.

22:27.556 --> 22:29.558
I haven't since he died.

22:30.142 --> 22:31.851
[sighs] I'm sorry,

22:31.852 --> 22:34.187
you just look so much like him.

22:34.188 --> 22:35.897
Except, uh, he was tall.

22:35.898 --> 22:38.024
And blonde. And hot.

22:38.025 --> 22:39.109
[Dudenoff chuckles]

22:40.694 --> 22:43.280
Oh Hell and <i>Perfect Strangers.</i>

22:44.323 --> 22:45.574
Huh...

22:46.825 --> 22:49.368
You know, uh,

22:49.369 --> 22:51.662
we have this little
card game Friday nights.

22:51.663 --> 22:53.664
[Helga]
<i>And that is how I met the gang.</i>

22:53.665 --> 22:56.209
- Why not?
- [Alfonso] Mm! Mm!

22:56.210 --> 22:58.836
[Helga]
<i>Yeah, I was there, too.</i>

22:58.837 --> 23:01.130
<i>I'm sure they didn't mention that.</i>

23:01.131 --> 23:03.299
- Wow.
- [Alfonso] Yeah!

23:03.300 --> 23:05.635
[Helga] <i>At first,
they were the nicest group of people</i>

23:05.636 --> 23:07.762
<i>I had met in New York City,</i>

23:07.763 --> 23:10.765
<i>a place I'd always wanted to call home.</i>

23:10.766 --> 23:13.351
[Inez]
Helga, so where do you live, honey?

23:13.352 --> 23:15.061
Uh, it's a wonderful little hovel.

23:15.062 --> 23:17.271
It's only 85 train stops away.

23:17.272 --> 23:18.814
You'd love it.

23:18.815 --> 23:21.734
<i>Then, he gave us these
nice cheap apartments,</i>

23:21.735 --> 23:24.153
<i>and he turned a bunch of perfect strangers</i>

23:24.154 --> 23:26.656
<i>into a family.</i>

23:26.657 --> 23:28.741
<i>But a few years later...</i>

23:28.742 --> 23:30.743
[♪ somber music playing]

23:30.744 --> 23:32.246
<i>...he was gone.</i>

23:33.247 --> 23:34.248
[keys jingle]

23:36.166 --> 23:38.209
<i>Said he felt bad doing it in a note,</i>

23:38.210 --> 23:40.837
<i>but he'd had enough of goodbyes.</i>

23:40.838 --> 23:42.130
<i>He was off to Portugal.</i>

23:42.881 --> 23:46.927
<i>After helping us with our dreams,
he wanted to live his.</i>

23:47.344 --> 23:49.637
- [power snaps, whirs down]
- [♪ music stops suddenly]

23:49.638 --> 23:51.722
- [lights click, power whirs back]
- [♪ music restarts]

23:51.723 --> 23:55.643
<i>I knew the power only surged
when the old incinerator was used,</i>

23:55.644 --> 23:58.646
<i>but I didn't suspect anything. Yet...</i>

23:58.647 --> 23:59.856
[podcast playing on phone]

23:59.857 --> 24:03.484
<i>Suddenly, we all went from
talking every day to nothing.</i>

24:03.485 --> 24:05.236
<i>Total silence.</i>

24:05.237 --> 24:07.655
<i>And then, your podcast started.</i>

24:07.656 --> 24:09.407
[Mabel] [on podcast]
<i>One thing was for sure</i>.

24:09.408 --> 24:12.076
<i>Someone in the Arconia
was hiding something.</i>

24:12.077 --> 24:14.829
[Oliver] [on podcast] <i>A homicidal freak
who poisoned a perfect,</i>

24:14.830 --> 24:16.331
<i>if gassy, dog.</i>

24:17.624 --> 24:20.168
[Helga]
<i>Everyone was acting so secretive.</i>

24:20.169 --> 24:21.252
Helga!

24:21.253 --> 24:23.004
[Helga]
<i>I listened to the podcast.</i>

24:23.005 --> 24:24.881
<i>All those unexplained things</i>

24:24.882 --> 24:27.258
<i>someone in the building
was doing to scare you.</i>

24:27.259 --> 24:31.596
<i>What if it was them trying to
cover up what they had done?</i>

24:31.597 --> 24:33.264
Let's play cards.

24:33.265 --> 24:35.683
[Helga]
<i>And I started to wonder.</i>

24:35.684 --> 24:37.768
[group murmuring]

24:37.769 --> 24:38.936
Please.

24:38.937 --> 24:41.731
[Helga]
<i>Why did the power surge that night?</i>

24:41.732 --> 24:45.777
<i>I couldn't prove they had anything
to do with Dudenoff's disappearance,</i>

24:47.362 --> 24:49.155
<i>but I knew in my bones</i>

24:49.156 --> 24:50.823
I had to move out.

24:50.824 --> 24:52.033
They killed him!

24:52.034 --> 24:53.492
- [Inez gasps]
- We didn't!

24:53.493 --> 24:56.412
- No, no! He went to Portugal.
- Dead men don't send ham!

24:56.413 --> 24:58.414
Then, what's this?

24:58.415 --> 24:59.957
I can't see.

24:59.958 --> 25:01.959
I actually don't know. What is that?

25:01.960 --> 25:04.295
- Dudenoff's prosthetic shoulder.
- [all gasp]

25:04.296 --> 25:07.507
It was in the incinerator.
You killed and burned him that night.

25:07.508 --> 25:09.967
And when Sazz figured it out,
you killed and burned her, too.

25:09.968 --> 25:12.803
And when we tried to look into that,
you tried to kill me!

25:12.804 --> 25:15.723
Yeah, another way to put that
is you actually shot me.

25:15.724 --> 25:18.309
What are we doing? What are we doing?
What are we doing?

25:18.310 --> 25:19.853
These people are murderers!

25:20.562 --> 25:24.315
I'm tired of being the nice guy here
with no temper!

25:24.316 --> 25:26.817
I'm a Canadian man connected

25:26.818 --> 25:29.195
to his rage right now!

25:29.196 --> 25:32.449
And [laughs] God, it feels so good!

25:33.408 --> 25:35.952
Charles, tantrum with me.

25:35.953 --> 25:37.662
No, no, no.

25:37.663 --> 25:40.665
They incinerated your friend, Charles.

25:40.666 --> 25:44.001
- And then plied you with word games...
- No. [laughs] No. No.

25:44.002 --> 25:46.547
...from the <i>New York Times!</i>

25:49.216 --> 25:51.384
[gasping, quiet wheezing]

25:51.385 --> 25:54.095
[♪ curious music playing]

25:54.096 --> 25:55.848
- So far, I'm underwhelmed.
- [coasters clatter]

25:56.765 --> 25:58.474
[gasping breaths]

25:58.475 --> 25:59.934
[Oliver]
Uh-huh...

25:59.935 --> 26:02.311
- [barely audible wheezing]
- Yes. Interesting.

26:02.312 --> 26:04.313
Is this how I find out he's a mime?

26:04.314 --> 26:06.816
No, no, no. We can't hear him,
but I'm so tuned into his character,

26:06.817 --> 26:09.694
I can feel his words. He's saying...

26:09.695 --> 26:11.988
[barely audible wheezing]

26:11.989 --> 26:13.866
..."These people killed Sazz!

26:14.741 --> 26:17.578
"I am steamed... and put out!

26:18.120 --> 26:20.454
- To some degree."
- [Vince] Oh, the hell with this!

26:20.455 --> 26:22.332
- Gimme that! Helga!
- [indistinct yelling]

26:23.417 --> 26:26.627
You're not the only one who got a note
the night that Dudenoff died.

26:26.628 --> 26:27.713
Now, everybody,

26:28.922 --> 26:30.716
come with me!

26:33.927 --> 26:36.930
[♪ mysterious music playing]

26:41.518 --> 26:43.520
We all got notes that night.

26:44.479 --> 26:46.481
Only ours were different.

26:49.067 --> 26:51.944
[Rudy] "You are cordially
invited to my funeral.

26:51.945 --> 26:54.239
Midnight, in the basement.
Don't tell Helga."

26:55.532 --> 26:57.742
- [Alfonso] What the fuck?
- Funeral?

26:57.743 --> 26:59.493
I don't like it.

26:59.494 --> 27:01.662
Come on. Let's go.

27:01.663 --> 27:04.540
- [Ana sighs]
- [Alfonso] Come on, come on.

27:04.541 --> 27:07.628
[♪ music building]

27:12.132 --> 27:13.633
[service elevator rattling]

27:13.634 --> 27:16.219
[overlapping chatter]

27:16.220 --> 27:18.679
Hey! Milton, what's going on?

27:18.680 --> 27:21.933
- Hey-- Okay--
- [overlapping chatter continues]

27:21.934 --> 27:24.393
Hey, can I just talk?! Can I?

27:24.394 --> 27:25.645
- Yeah.
- Of course.

27:25.646 --> 27:27.104
[Dudenoff]
Uh, so,

27:27.105 --> 27:30.567
you know I'm always saying a movie
is only as good as its cast?

27:32.236 --> 27:34.738
Now, I'm just a teacher.
I never got to make...

27:35.364 --> 27:36.615
my own movie.

27:37.241 --> 27:38.741
But I'll tell you this.

27:38.742 --> 27:41.661
If our lives were a movie...

27:41.662 --> 27:43.371
[laughs]

27:43.372 --> 27:45.581
I cast the shit outta this one.

27:45.582 --> 27:47.042
[soft laughter]

27:48.335 --> 27:51.630
Professor, what exactly are we doing here?

27:52.297 --> 27:54.299
Well, uh...

27:55.467 --> 27:57.468
I-I have some medical news.

27:57.469 --> 27:59.555
[weak laugh] Um...

28:00.681 --> 28:02.265
I'm an old guy, so, you know,

28:02.266 --> 28:05.351
it's not like <i>Terms of Endearment</i> sad
or anything,

28:05.352 --> 28:08.145
but, you know, I-- Uh...

28:08.146 --> 28:10.022
they tell me I've, uh,
only got a few months.

28:10.023 --> 28:11.649
- [shocked chatter]
- And so--

28:11.650 --> 28:15.403
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Uh, you know, when I'm gone...

28:15.404 --> 28:17.363
[♪ somber music playing]

28:17.364 --> 28:20.658
...uh, this building,
they're gonna swoop in and,

28:20.659 --> 28:24.370
you know, tear our cast apart. But,

28:24.371 --> 28:26.664
I have a workaround.

28:26.665 --> 28:28.250
And, uh...

28:30.544 --> 28:34.506
and it's that you will all keep me alive.

28:36.091 --> 28:37.842
W-Well, I mean, actually no

28:37.843 --> 28:41.429
'cause I've just taken
a hell of a lot of pills.

28:41.430 --> 28:42.722
[shocked chatter]

28:42.723 --> 28:45.016
I want you, tonight,

28:45.017 --> 28:47.518
to put my body in the incinerator!

28:47.519 --> 28:49.478
- [all yelling]
- [Dudenoff] Yes! Yes!

28:49.479 --> 28:53.191
And then, I want you to cash
my social security checks,

28:53.192 --> 28:56.278
and I want you to tell everybody
I just moved to Portugal.

28:57.738 --> 28:58.739
[sighs]

28:59.740 --> 29:01.157
And you...

29:01.158 --> 29:03.160
you can't tell Helga.

29:03.994 --> 29:07.122
I'm just gonna record a message,
you know, in case, uh,

29:07.748 --> 29:11.042
you know, she finds out,
and then, she won't blame you.

29:11.043 --> 29:12.376
- We can call an ambulance.
- Yeah--

29:12.377 --> 29:14.963
No, come on, let me do this.
Just let-- Just let me do this.

29:16.715 --> 29:19.133
Please. And then, you know, afterwards,

29:19.134 --> 29:21.094
then let's just all hug and shit, okay?

29:21.678 --> 29:23.304
Hey, so, Vince, come on.

29:23.305 --> 29:24.389
[snaps fingers]

29:24.973 --> 29:27.184
Chop, chop. Let's shoot this thing.

29:28.185 --> 29:30.061
Come on. One take.

29:30.062 --> 29:33.564
[♪ somber music continues]

29:33.565 --> 29:35.566
- [clicks knob, film whirs]
- [Alfonso] It's okay.

29:35.567 --> 29:36.984
It's okay. It's okay.

29:36.985 --> 29:38.529
[camera whirring]

29:42.658 --> 29:46.078
♪

29:46.286 --> 29:49.289
[projector whirring]

29:50.749 --> 29:53.544
[Dudenoff] [on film]
<i>Hey, Helga. I know you're angry</i>.

29:54.628 --> 29:57.046
<i>But, you know, you had such a, uh,</i>

29:57.047 --> 30:00.425
<i>hard time bouncing back after your dad
that I-I had this...</i>

30:01.593 --> 30:04.262
<i>stupid thought that maybe I could...</i>

30:04.263 --> 30:06.849
<i>shield you from another death.</i>

30:07.641 --> 30:08.683
<i>But, if you're watching this,</i>

30:08.684 --> 30:11.270
<i>then, you know,
my master plan has gone to hell.</i>

30:12.604 --> 30:14.022
<i>And, hopefully, I haven't.</i>

30:14.690 --> 30:17.108
<i>What can a guy do but try, right?</i>

30:17.109 --> 30:19.194
<i>Here's looking at you, kid.</i>

30:21.071 --> 30:22.072
[film crackles]

30:23.073 --> 30:24.074
[projector clicking]

30:25.659 --> 30:28.286
- We're so sorry, baby.
- [Helga sniffling]

30:28.287 --> 30:31.664
Yeah. It's, uh, it's what he wanted,

30:31.665 --> 30:32.875
to keep us all together.

30:33.750 --> 30:35.126
[Vince]
Move on back in with us.

30:35.127 --> 30:37.004
- Please.
- Please.

30:37.671 --> 30:40.464
It is the only place in New York
where I can have a pig.

30:40.465 --> 30:42.466
- [laughter]
- [Mabel] Wait.

30:42.467 --> 30:45.720
Helga's not Rudy's ex-girlfriend?

30:45.721 --> 30:47.013
That was another lie?

30:47.014 --> 30:49.473
Yeah, in addition to
setting a human on fire,

30:49.474 --> 30:51.559
we also lied about me having a girlfriend.

30:51.560 --> 30:53.144
May God have mercy.

30:53.145 --> 30:55.772
- [♪ gentle music playing]
- [Helga sniffles]

30:56.815 --> 30:57.816
[Mabel sighs]

31:00.611 --> 31:01.612
[Eva]
Hmm.

31:04.364 --> 31:06.325
So, these are not murderers.

31:06.950 --> 31:08.160
[Eva]
No, but...

31:08.911 --> 31:10.203
we've got one hell of a podcast.

31:10.204 --> 31:12.830
- [multitool clicks]
- [Alfonso] [auto-tuned] <i>And, yes,</i>

31:12.831 --> 31:16.000
<i>we've been keeping up the ruse
and cashing his checks.</i>

31:16.001 --> 31:17.211
Oh God. We're going to jail.

31:18.504 --> 31:19.795
- Well...
- [clicks button]

31:19.796 --> 31:21.839
No, you're not.

31:21.840 --> 31:26.178
Guys, we used to be three lonely weirdos
living in the Arconia.

31:27.554 --> 31:30.807
The podcast brought us together.
I don't wanna use it to tear them apart.

31:32.142 --> 31:34.144
- [Westies murmuring]
- [quietly] Bless you.

31:36.563 --> 31:39.774
So, humanity's more important
to you than the podcast?

31:39.775 --> 31:41.151
- What a revelation.
- [Eva] Hmm.

31:43.403 --> 31:47.156
Okay, what if it's not three losers,
but, like, a family of losers

31:47.157 --> 31:50.619
who wants to make the world a better place
before two of them die?

31:51.119 --> 31:52.578
That's one way to look at it.

31:52.579 --> 31:53.663
Yeah. Well, I have more.

31:53.664 --> 31:55.081
- You wanna hear more?
- [Mabel] No thanks.

31:55.082 --> 31:57.334
Speaking of family, I should tell you

31:58.252 --> 32:00.294
that I had my assistant's assistant

32:00.295 --> 32:02.880
book you a wedding atop...

32:02.881 --> 32:05.883
the Empire State Building,
encircled by a fleet of hot air balloons.

32:05.884 --> 32:07.844
- No, no. I--
- Don't worry. I-'m gonna...

32:07.845 --> 32:09.387
I'll pay for it.

32:09.388 --> 32:12.683
I wish I could tell you this
gives me joy, but it doesn't.

32:13.684 --> 32:15.685
You are not the romantic
I thought you were,

32:15.686 --> 32:18.271
and I don't know how I'm gonna play you

32:18.272 --> 32:20.356
or respect you.

32:20.357 --> 32:23.067
So, [sighs] here we are.

32:23.068 --> 32:25.653
Well, thank you, Zachary, for those...

32:25.654 --> 32:27.780
lovely words. But,

32:27.781 --> 32:31.493
Loretta and I shall marry here,
in the Arconia.

32:31.994 --> 32:33.787
This is where we fell in love,

32:35.038 --> 32:36.706
and I want a marriage

32:36.707 --> 32:39.333
where we fall in love every day

32:39.334 --> 32:42.129
for the rest of our very long lives.

32:43.463 --> 32:44.922
You...

32:44.923 --> 32:47.049
adorable baloney loaf.

32:47.050 --> 32:48.802
- [weak laugh]
- You...

32:49.219 --> 32:51.387
beautiful bitchy...

32:51.388 --> 32:54.015
baloney loaf.

32:54.016 --> 32:55.725
Do you know what a baloney loaf is?

32:55.726 --> 32:56.810
Uh--

32:58.020 --> 33:00.022
[♪ gentle music playing]

33:00.606 --> 33:02.524
You are a romantic.

33:03.108 --> 33:04.276
- [smacks]
- [Oliver snorts]

33:05.110 --> 33:07.613
You got me in touch with my emotions.
Thank you.

33:08.488 --> 33:10.781
Well, it was an honor playing a small part

33:10.782 --> 33:13.242
in bringing out your true self.

33:13.243 --> 33:15.870
And Charles, I won't
alienate your audience

33:15.871 --> 33:18.749
- by putting any of it on film.
- [elevator dings]

33:23.045 --> 33:24.546
- Bye.
- Bye.

33:25.214 --> 33:26.215
Bye.

33:27.841 --> 33:29.842
- [Oliver sighs]
- You good?

33:29.843 --> 33:31.637
[Mabel]
Yeah, I'm good.

33:35.265 --> 33:38.935
[Dudenoff] <i>Whether or not everyone makes
it back to shore in the movie</i> Lifeboat...

33:38.936 --> 33:42.856
♪

33:45.108 --> 33:47.110
<i>...I'll leave for you to discover.</i>

33:48.612 --> 33:52.698
<i>But what the film is really about
is found families</i>,

33:52.699 --> 33:55.284
<i>fighting together for their survival</i>

33:55.285 --> 33:58.704
<i>in waters that can be
really tough to get through</i>

33:58.705 --> 34:00.206
<i>if you're all alone.</i>

34:00.207 --> 34:03.293
[♪ gentle music continues]

34:11.385 --> 34:14.554
[Mabel] <i>In the end, there was
no murder in the West Tower.</i>

34:14.555 --> 34:16.722
<i>Just a guy who moved to Portugal</i>

34:16.723 --> 34:19.392
<i>- and made a family out of strangers.</i>
- [recorder beeps]

34:19.393 --> 34:21.060
Well, found family,

34:21.061 --> 34:25.524
we buried a great podcast story
and are back to square one.

34:25.941 --> 34:26.942
[drops cards]

34:27.943 --> 34:31.904
[sighs] Why can't we ever get a ding-dong
when we run out of leads?

34:31.905 --> 34:33.364
[knocking on door]

34:33.365 --> 34:35.450
Oh! A knock-knock ding-dong!

34:35.993 --> 34:37.035
[Oliver sighs]

34:39.413 --> 34:41.205
- Think he's got any Gut Milk in there?
- [door opens]

34:41.206 --> 34:43.791
I already checked the fridge.
He just has beer.

34:43.792 --> 34:45.919
- [Hammy oinking]
- Look who's here.

34:46.587 --> 34:49.005
Oh, hey, Helga.
I see you got your pig back.

34:49.006 --> 34:52.884
Yes! I'm grateful to the angry man
who reluctantly returned her to me.

34:52.885 --> 34:54.135
I think his name is Howard?

34:54.136 --> 34:55.678
[Hammy grunts]

34:55.679 --> 34:57.680
I didn't want to bring it up
among the reunions,

34:57.681 --> 35:01.310
but I wanted to tell you something
about your friend, Sazz.

35:02.102 --> 35:04.228
Wait. You actually knew her?

35:04.229 --> 35:06.397
Yes. She was on the ham radio,

35:06.398 --> 35:09.358
asking about all these huge plot holes
you had in your podcast.

35:09.359 --> 35:11.319
- Not holes.
- Oh!

35:11.320 --> 35:14.822
You're how Sazz knew about
all the West Tower stuff in her notes.

35:14.823 --> 35:16.574
There was another thing though.

35:16.575 --> 35:20.870
She talked about a stuntman
on a movie called <i>Project Ronkonkoma.</i>

35:20.871 --> 35:23.289
She said he was her protégé,

35:23.290 --> 35:26.459
but that he had messed up pretty badly
and he was harassing her.

35:26.460 --> 35:30.547
She said, "He's dangerous,
and he's gonna be the death of me."

35:31.715 --> 35:34.425
- What's <i>Project Ronkonkoma?</i>
- Check IMDb.

35:34.426 --> 35:36.511
- That's a website.
- I know what IMDb is.

35:36.512 --> 35:38.346
My agent says he's gonna get me on it.

35:38.347 --> 35:40.932
Here we go! <i>Project Ronkonkoma.</i>

35:40.933 --> 35:42.433
Who's the stuntperson?

35:42.434 --> 35:44.644
Is it someone we can talk to?

35:44.645 --> 35:47.439
- Not exactly.
- [Hammy oinks]

35:47.814 --> 35:50.942
[medical devices beeping, hissing]

35:50.943 --> 35:53.278
[♪ music building]

35:55.572 --> 35:58.575
[♪ dramatic music playing]

36:20.097 --> 36:23.559
♪

36:47.541 --> 36:48.624
[♪ music ends]

36:48.625 --> 36:51.628
[♪ fanfare playing]
